Edge sharpened but very worn.

Socketed object terminating in 2 triangular plates, slightly spaced and each with two perforations, intended to hold save missing object (? a flat piece of metal). This is the best-made of the three such objects known, the triangular blades having bevelled edges, and two well-made rivet-holes. At the base of the socket on rivet hole, which does not appear on the other side.
Broken; butt end only.
Typology: "...a much honeycombed" ..."fragment of an early celt..." composed with a flat axe from Maddox Barrow, Bere, Dorset

collection: Croydon Natural History - Scientific Soc. Collection

description: Plates are crushed together, but the line indicating the inner edges can be clearly seen. The upper part of them is slightly bent over to one side. Base of the socket it broken. The remaining piece includes one rivet hole.
